The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Rush for divine wedding
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           Rush for divine wedding
          OUR CORRESPONDENT                              
	Sambalpur, June 8: Sheetal shasthi, a religious ceremony symbolising the marriage of Shiv with Parvati, was held in Sambalpur today.         
	Hundreds of residents of the town and several devotees from different parts of the state travelled miles to reach Sambalpur today to take part in the auspicious event.         
	The religious ceremony is held on the sixth day of Jaishtha in shukla pakshya in both individual homes and temples.         
	The towns men today donned the role of the father and got their daughter (Parvati) married off in a mock wedding that is complete with gifts for both the bride and the groom.         
	Sambalpur has been witnessing this unique ritual that is also seen as an alliance between prakriti (nature) and purusha (mankind) every year.         
	At the end of the puja or the marriage, the blessings of deva dampati or the divine couple is sought by hundreds of faithful who throng homes and temples to witness the marriage on this day.         
	After the marriages are completed at temples or homes, the bride and the groom are prepared for their return in mammoth processions that often carry on till late night. The procession is the main attraction of the ritual where traditional performers and dancers escort the gods back to their temple abodes with music, drums and dance performances.                                                                                                                                                                          
